1. hostname => Show or change a system’s hostname.

2. pwd => Print the current working directory’s path.

3. echo => Output text on the terminal.

4. ls => List the contents of a directory. -a, -l, -F, -R, -r, -i are some of the options that can be used with ls command.

5. cd => Change the current directory.

6. mkdir => Create a new directory.

7. cp => Copy files or directories.

8. mv => Move or rename files or directories.

9. rm => Delete files or directories.

10. touch => Create an empty file or update an existing file’s modification date.

11. cat => Read and output the contents of a file. '-n' flag will display line numbers.

12. rmdir => Delete directories which are empty.

13. head => By default displays the first 10 lines of a file.

14. tail => By default displays the last 10 lines of a file.

15. tree => Display a hierarchical listing of a directory tree.

16. find => Traverse a file system tree and search for files matching a specific set of criteria.

17. file => Display the type of file, directory or etc. A quick way to identify the file type.

18. grep =>  Use to search the content in a file. One of the widely used command.

19. type => Show how a specific command is executed.

20. env => Display the current environment.

21. export => Make local variables available to subprocesses.

22. unset => Remove a variable.

23. kill => Use to terminate a process. The kill command allows you to send signals to processes based on their process ID (PID).

24. killall => The killall command is a powerful way to stop processes by using their names rather than the PID numbers. You can use wildcards as well.

25. df => Display how much disk space is available on an individual device. Use -h to get the output in human readable format (M for megabytes, etc)

26. du => The du command shows the disk usage for a specifi c directory (by default, the current directory)

27. sort => It sorts data in a file.

